    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-09-28T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-09-28T08:00:00-05:00" n="199"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d199">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">875.01/9–2844: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Alexander C. Kirk</persName>,
                        Political Adviser, Allied Force Headquarters, to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caserta</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-09-28T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 28, 1944—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4:07 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>575. Reference my 451, September 19.<note n="33" xml:id="d199fn33">Telegram not
                        printed.</note> BAF Policy Committee is being asked to consider desirability
                    of extending aid to LNC beyond time of German withdrawal from Albania on grounds
                    its political opponents will inherit surplus German arms. This is frankly
                    recognized as direct intervention in Albania’s internal affairs and seems
                    unnecessary since most Allied sources in Bari now believe that civil war can be
                    avoided except possibly in a few areas in northeast and Kossovo. As reported in
                    our No. 572, September 28,<note n="34" xml:id="d199fn34">Not printed.</note> the
                    recent disunity and distintegration among Nationalist elements and desertions to
                    LNC make it unlikely that German arms could be used effectively even if left
                    behind in anti-LNC hands. Moreover, it is assumed some Allied occupational
                    troops will arrive in time.</p>
                <pb facs="0292" n="280" xml:id="pg_280"/>
                <p>In addition, LNC has lately given indication of a softening attitude towards its
                    political opponents, Kupi excluded.</p>
                <p>The Department’s comments would be appreciated as soon as possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
